10119nam a22011895i 9780520924932DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209249327 a10.1525/97805209249322doi  a(DE-B1597)648937  a(OCoLC)1414456813  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHM1136b.N37 2000eb 7aSCI0700002bisacsh04a303.6/92211 aAureli, Filippo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNatural Conflict Resolution /cFilippo Aureli; ed. by Filippo Aureli. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (424 p.) :b38 b/w photographs, 31 line illustrations, 19 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER I Why Natural Conflict Resolution? -- tPART I History -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 2 The First Kiss: Foundations of Conflict Resolution Research in Animals -- tCHAPTER 3 Conflict Management in Children and Adolescents -- tCHAPTER 4 Law, Love, and Reconciliation: Searching for Natural Conflict Resolution in Homo Sapiens -- tPART II Controlling Aggression -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 5 Dominance and Communication: Conflict Management in Various Social Settings -- tCHAPTER 6 Covariation of Conflict Management Patterns across Macaque Species -- tCHAPTER 7 Coping with Crowded Conditions -- tCHAPTER 8 The Peacefulness of Cooperatively Breeding Primates -- tPART III Repairing the Damage -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 9 Reconciliation and Relationship Qualities -- tCHAPTER 10 The Role of Emotion in Conflict and Conflict Resolution -- tCHAPTER 11 Beyond the Primates: Expanding the Reconciliation Horizon -- tCHAPTER 12 A Multicultural View of Peacemaking among Young Children -- tPART IV Triadic Affairs -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 13 Conflict Management via Third Parties: Post-Conflict Affiliation of the Aggressor -- tCHAPTER 14 Redirection, Consolation, and Male Policing: How Targets of Aggression Interact with Bystanders -- tPART V Ecological and Cultural Contexts -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 15 The Natural History of Valuable Relationships in Primates -- tCHAPTER 16 Conflict Management in Cross-Cultural Perspective -- tCHAPTER 17 The Evolution and Development of Morality -- tConclusion -- tCHAPTER 18 Shared Principles and Unanswered Questions -- tAppendixes -- tAPPENDIX A The Occurrence of Reconciliation in Nonhuman Primates -- tAPPENDIX B Key Terms Used in the Volume -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAggression and competition are customarily presented as the natural state of affairs in both human society and the animal kingdom. Yet, as this book shows, our species relies heavily on cooperation for survival as do many others—from wolves and dolphins to monkeys and apes. A distinguished group of fifty-two authors, including many of the world's leading experts on human and animal behavior, review evidence from multiple disciplines on natural conflict resolution, making the case that reconciliation and compromise are as much a part of our heritage as is waging war. Chimpanzees kiss and embrace after a fight. Children will appeal to fairness when fighting over a toy. Spotted hyenas, usually thought to be a particularly aggressive species, use reconciliation to restore damaged relationships. As these studies show, there are sound evolutionary reasons for these peacekeeping tendencies. This book also addresses the cultural, ecological, cognitive, emotional, and moral perspectives of conflict resolution.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConflict management. 0aGestion des conflits. 4aLif